Obviously Trump Media & Technology Group Corp. should sell stock. It is a h=
ighly valued public company stapled to a teeny little operating business: L=
ast quarter it had=C2=A0revenue of $770,500 from selling ads on its social =
media site, and its operating cash flow=C2=A0was negative $9.3 million.
  [1]
 Its equity market capitalization is around $7 billion. People value the st=
ock at $7=C2=A0billion not because they project high future operating cash =
flows but because Trump Media has =E2=80=9CTrump=E2=80=9D in the name, is l=
argely owned by Donald Trump, and represents a bet on his electoral fortune=
s and general newsworthiness. Those have gone up recently. Converting Trump=
=E2=80=99s newsworthiness into money is, as far as I can tell, the=C2=A0poi=
nt=C2=A0of Trump Media, and now is the time.Traditionally the way meme-y co=
mpanies raise money is with at-the-market stock offerings. In an ATM offeri=
ng, the company hires a broker, and the broker sells some stock, at market =
prices, over the course of days or weeks. This is different from a traditio=
nal underwritten offering, in which the company=E2=80=99s investment bank m=
arkets the stock to big investors, builds an order book, and then sells a c=
hunk of stock all at once, at a single price, to all of those investors. Th=
e problem with a traditional underwriting, for a meme stock, is that your b=
anks call up all the professional investors and say =E2=80=9Chey do you wan=
t to buy this stock at a crazy price?=E2=80=9D and the investors say =E2=80=
=9Cno I do not.=E2=80=9D Being a meme stock means that=C2=A0retail=C2=A0inv=
estors are buying the stock at a crazy price, and the big investment banks =
can=E2=80=99t really call them all. So meme stocks do ATM offerings, so the=
y can sell the stock directly on the exchange, where the retail investors a=
re buying it at crazy prices.And so many meme and meme-adjacent stocks =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0Tesla and GameStop=C2=A0and AMC and Hertz and Bed Bath & Beyond=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0have done ATMs, to take advantage of high trading prices to=
 raise money for themselves.Trump Media, though, can=E2=80=99t. Trump Media=
 went public in March by merging with a special purpose acquisition company=
 called Digital World Acquisition Corp. The US Securities and Exchange Comm=
ission rules only allow companies that have been public for at least 12 mon=
ths to do at-the-market offerings, so Trump Media can=E2=80=99t do one unti=
l next March.
  [2]
There is a solution. The solution is:=09Trump Media sells stock to=C2=A0one=
=C2=A0investor, over time, at market-based prices.=09Each time that=C2=A0on=
e=C2=A0investor buys stock from Trump Media, it can immediately turn around=
 and resell it, on the stock exchange, at market prices.It=E2=80=99s meme-s=
tock intermediation, an at-the-market offering done through one investor. T=
here are a couple of ways to do this =E2=80=94=C2=A0Bed Bath & Beyond once =
did a pretty complicated one =E2=80=94=C2=A0but a simple one is called an =
=E2=80=9Cequity line of credit=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cstandby equity purchase=
 agreement=E2=80=9D: The investor signs a deal with the company saying =E2=
=80=9Cyou can sell us up to $X worth of stock, over time, whenever you want=
, and we=E2=80=99ll pay you the market price for it less a discount for our=
 trouble.=E2=80=9D And then whenever the company wants money, it calls up t=
he investor and says =E2=80=9Cokay $10 million today,=E2=80=9D and the inve=
stor sells $10 million worth of stock into the market and pays the company =
$10 million, less its fee. And if the market is good and the company wants =
a lot of money, it makes those calls every day, and pretty soon the investo=
r has sold a lot of stock and the company has raised a lot of money.In thes=
e deals, the investor is often Yorkville Advisors. We talked in 2021 about =
an equity line of credit that Yorkville did for Lordstown Motors Corp., ano=
ther recent SPAC company. And this week Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Bailey Lipschul=
tz reports:A little-known New Jersey investment manager that focuses on fin=
ancing micro-cap and small-cap companies has found its most high-profile de=
al: Donald Trump=E2=80=99s media startup.Yorkville Advisors, which operates=
 out of Mountainside, about an hour=E2=80=99s drive from Wall Street, recen=
tly inked an agreement with Trump Media & Technology Group Corp. that could=
 raise $2.5 billion for the former president=E2=80=99s company. The owner o=
f Truth Social registered 38 million shares late Monday as part of the pact=
, according to a filing.The deal is a classic Yorkville arrangement. It=E2=
=80=99s set to provide much-needed funds to a company that went public by m=
erging with a blank-check vehicle. Yorkville has previously backed clients =
in cash-burning sectors such as electric vehicles, and has worked with a ha=
ndful of high-profile companies whose stock has fluctuated wildly, such as =
VinFast Auto Ltd., and even a few like Lordstown Motors that have crashed.A=
s part of the pact, known as a standby equity purchase agreement, Trump Med=
ia has the right but not the obligation to sell shares to Yorkville to rais=
e money for working capital and general purposes. In return for signing up,=
 Yorkville gets 200,000 common shares =E2=80=94 worth $7.4 million based on=
 Tuesday=E2=80=99s trading, after an 8.5% decline trimmed Trump Media=E2=80=
=99s weekly gains.Yorkville has participated in countless deals that involv=
e so-called de-SPACs, where a private firm goes public by merging with a sp=
ecial purpose acquisition company.One obvious point here is that Yorkville =
is not going to=C2=A0invest=C2=A0$2.5 billion in Trump Media.=C2=A0Yorkvill=
e=E2=80=99s total assets under management are about $323 million. Yorkville=
 is in the moving business, not the storage business: Any stock that it buy=
s from Trump Media will be sold directly into the market.Here is the prospe=
ctus for the deal; here is the actual agreement. The mechanism is:=09Yorkvi=
lle commits to buying up to $2.5 billion of Trump Media stock, at Trump Med=
ia=E2=80=99s discretion, over the next three years.=09Before 9 a.m. on any =
trading day, Trump Media can send Yorkville a notice saying =E2=80=9Cwe wan=
t to sell _____ shares,=E2=80=9D with a number of its choosing in the blank=
 (capped at the daily trading volume of the stock
  [3]
).=C2=A0=09Trump Media immediately hands the shares to Yorkville,
  [4]
=C2=A0so it can sell them.=09Yorkville sells the shares over three days, st=
arting on the day of the notice. Or, I mean, that is not a=C2=A0requirement=
=C2=A0of the contract, and the prospectus says:=C2=A0=E2=80=9COur registrat=
ion of the securities covered by this prospectus does not mean that Yorkvil=
le will offer or sell any of the Shares.=E2=80=9D But what else would it do=
?=09At the end of the three days, Yorkville pays Trump Media for the shares=
. The price is the lowest=C2=A0of the daily volume weighted average prices =
of the shares over the three-day period, minus a 2.75% fee.So Yorkville get=
s paid (1) an upfront commitment fee of 200,000 shares, (2) a 2.75% discoun=
t on the shares it buys, and (3) some optionality from being able to sell t=
he shares over three days, but paying the=C2=A0lowest=C2=A0price over those=
 three days. It looks a lot like an at-the-market offering =E2=80=94=C2=A0i=
n which a broker takes a fee to sell stock at the company=E2=80=99s instruc=
tions =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is just different enough to be allowed under SE=
C rules.Lipschultz also reports:Investors backing Donald Trump=E2=80=99s me=
dia startup may see their stake diluted after the company registered 38 mil=
lion shares as part of a financing pact with Yorkville Advisors. ...The reg=
istration starts the clock on the potential dilution of existing shareholde=
rs related to the deal, which allows Yorkville to buy as much as $2.5 billi=
on of stock from the owner of Truth Social at a discount.This is the part o=
f meme stocks that I understand the least. What is =E2=80=9Cdilution=E2=80=
=9D? I feel like the standard corporate finance view is that selling shares=
 for more than they are worth is accretive:=C2=A0Right now, each Trump Medi=
a share represents 1/189,941,870th
  [5]
 of a company that sells maybe $1 million worth of internet ads per quarter=
; if this deal goes well, each share will represent a somewhat smaller frac=
tion of (1) that business plus (2) $2.5 billion of cash. That=E2=80=99s bet=
ter!But I suppose if each share of Trump Media stock is in fact a somewhat =
scarce token representing the value of attention to Donald Trump, then mint=
ing more of them reduces their rarity =E2=80=94=C2=A0and raising cash doesn=
=E2=80=99t actually help existing investors, since the business is not real=
ly the point.
