      SpaceX/xAI funds
   =20
 =20
A simple model of modern retail investing is:=09Low-cost passive index inve=
sting is on the rise: You can buy all of the stocks in the market, get the =
market return and pay fees of roughly zero.=09Private=C2=A0investing is on =
the rise: Big famous tech companies stay private longer, private credit is =
hot, and the pool of =E2=80=9Caccredited investors=E2=80=9D (people rich en=
ough to buy private investments under SEC rules) keeps growing, so more peo=
ple have the ability and the desire to invest in private companies and fund=
s.=09Regular old mutual funds =E2=80=94=C2=A0where you pay fees to a profes=
sional manager to pick public stocks for you =E2=80=94=C2=A0are on the decl=
ine, because index funds are cheaper and private investments are more excit=
ing.So if you run a mutual fund company, and you don=E2=80=99t have the sca=
le to run index funds at near-zero fees, you are having a tough time. The o=
bvious answer is to get into private funds: Private markets aren=E2=80=99t =
really indexed, so you don=E2=80=99t face any competition from cheap index =
funds.=C2=A0Here=E2=80=99s a variation on that approach:Ron Baron, an early=
 backer of Tesla Inc., is deepening his embrace of Chief Executive Officer =
Elon Musk by setting up partnerships that would permit clients to invest in=
 two of the billionaire=E2=80=99s private ventures.Baron Capital Management=
 formed a pair of funds in recent months to invest solely in Musk=E2=80=99s=
 xAI, the artificial intelligence startup that raised some $6 billion throu=
gh a private stock sale earlier this year. Baron=E2=80=99s firm also starte=
d a private partnership to buy more shares of Space Exploration Technologie=
s, Musk=E2=80=99s rocket and satellite company. ...The Baron vehicles =E2=
=80=A6 are forgoing high compensation for a different sort of payoff: a wag=
er that providing access to SpaceX and xAI will raise the firm=E2=80=99s pr=
ofile among family offices and private bank clients who might later invest =
in its mutual funds.=E2=80=9CWe are doing this because we want people to kn=
ow about our mutual funds,=E2=80=9D Baron, 81, said in a telephone intervie=
w. =E2=80=9CI want my business to last for 100 years.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6The=
 money raised by the private partnerships could help offset outflows that B=
aron Capital=E2=80=99s mutual funds have experienced since the start of 202=
2, said Adam Sabban, a senior analyst at Morningstar. Many other stock-pick=
ing funds are caught in the same bind, Sabban said.=E2=80=9CBecause of inde=
x funds taking over, pretty much every active equity shop is fighting an up=
hill battle at the moment,=E2=80=9D he said.I guess? =E2=80=9CWe gave you e=
xposure to SpaceX, which is more than your index fund ever did for you, so =
the least you can do for us is buy some of our mutual funds.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
 =20
   =20
      Carlos Watson
   =20
 =20
I guess it is fairly common for people who are arrested for lying to invest=
ors to defend themselves by saying =E2=80=9Coh come on,=C2=A0everybody=C2=
=A0lies to investors, there=E2=80=99s nothing wrong with that.=E2=80=9D Pre=
sumably they even believe it? You don=E2=80=99t want to think of yourself a=
s a bad person; you want to believe that what you are doing is the norm, pa=
rt of doing business, what everyone else does, tacitly socially accepted be=
havior. =E2=80=9COh come on,=E2=80=9D you tell yourself, and then also late=
r a jury, =E2=80=9Ceverybody exaggerates a little bit here and there, nobod=
y takes financial statements all that seriously, this isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0fr=
aud, it=E2=80=99s just=C2=A0business.=E2=80=9DWhile I generally think that =
everything is securities fraud, nonetheless I sometimes have a certain amou=
nt of sympathy for that defense. A while back there was a wave of prosecuti=
ons of bond traders who lied to customers about the prices they paid for bo=
nds, and their defense was =E2=80=9Coh come on, we were playing poker, ever=
yone hides information, I was allowed to be cute about what I paid.=E2=80=
=9D And it seems to me true that,=C2=A0if=C2=A0the market norm was that you=
 could lie about the price you paid,=C2=A0then=C2=A0those lies would not be=
 material to your customers =E2=80=94=C2=A0they would know to ignore them =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0so they wouldn=E2=80=99t be fraud. This defense had a mixed =
record at trial, but many convictions were ultimately reversed on appeal, s=
o the argument kind of worked.Or there are some startup fraud cases, and th=
ere does seem to me to be=C2=A0something=C2=A0to the theory that all ambiti=
ous startup founders have to be somewhat out of touch with reality: They ha=
ve to see the world not as it is, but as they want it to be, and convince i=
nvestors of their vision. If it all works out, they are visionaries. If it =
doesn=E2=80=99t, they were lying. There is some moral luck involved: =E2=80=
=9CFake it til you make it=E2=80=9D leads to either success or jail.That on=
e doesn=E2=80=99t go all that well with juries, though:Ozy Media and Chief =
Executive Officer Carlos Watson were found guilty of defrauding investors i=
n a case featuring allegations Watson coached his co-founder to impersonate=
 a YouTube executive to get Goldman Sachs bankers to back the media startup=
.A jury delivered its verdict on the former TV host and Ozy Media Tuesday i=
n Brooklyn federal court following a six-week trial. Watson was immediately=
 taken into custody after his bail was revoked by the judge.The company and=
 Watson, 54, were convicted of conspiracy to commit wire fraud and securiti=
es fraud, while Watson was also convicted of aggravated identity theft.We t=
alked about that YouTube impersonation in 2021, because it was amazing. (Wa=
tson=E2=80=99s defense was that his co-founder, Samir Rao, did that imperso=
nation without his permission, though prosecutors =E2=80=9Ccited text messa=
ges he sent to Mr. Rao during the call =E2=80=94 among them, =E2=80=98use t=
he right pronouns=E2=80=99 =E2=80=94 that, they claimed, amounted to instru=
ctions for what to say.=E2=80=9D)But when Watson was indicted last year, it=
 was=C2=A0mostly=C2=A0for other stuff, for telling potential investors lies=
 about the company=E2=80=99s earnings and other investors. Part of his defe=
nse to those charges was that actually accounting is complicated, other peo=
ple prepared the financials, and he always thought he was telling the truth=
. But part of it was oh, come on, startups always lie to investors. Watson=
=E2=80=99s lawyers complained that prosecutors were =E2=80=9Cstretching the=
 law beyond recognition in an attempt to criminalize what is at worst commo=
nplace puffery,=E2=80=9D that other digital media companies =E2=80=9Creport=
edly =E2=80=94 and in some cases, admittedly =E2=80=94 engaged in conduct t=
hat differs from the conduct charged in Mr. Watson's Indictment in only one=
 way: their conduct was, by orders of magnitude, far more egregious,=E2=80=
=9D and that he was just using =E2=80=9Ctactics commonly used by entreprene=
urs to gain the attention of Silicon Valley and other venture capitalists w=
ho provide capital investments for start-ups to launch and grow.=E2=80=9DBu=
t =E2=80=9Cehhh everybody else does it=E2=80=9D is not really a defense. Ev=
en if it=E2=80=99s true, the prosecutors get to choose to make an example o=
f someone. And whether or not lots of early-stage startups somewhat exagger=
ate=C2=A0their financial health, really none of them=C2=A0impersonate custo=
mers on due diligence calls. When Watson was indicted, I wrote:Is Ozy the f=
irst private company to send an investor a pitch deck that inflated its Ebi=
tda by 70% or 80%? Probably not, no. But =E2=80=A6=C2=A0if you do a fraud t=
hat is so egregious and hilarious that it becomes national news, you will g=
et in trouble. If you are marking up your Ebitda a bit in pitches to privat=
e investors, prosecutors and the SEC might never hear about it, but if you =
are doing multiple elaborate impersonations to raise money you are eventual=
ly going to attract attention.It is hard to get away from that.
