ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Last quarter</a> it=
 had=C2=A0revenue of $770,500 from selling ads on its social media site, an=
d its operating cash flow=C2=A0was negative $9.3 million.<a class=3D"footno=
te-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important;=
 display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> Its equity market capitalization is around $7 billion. People value th=
e stock at $7=C2=A0billion not because they project high future operating c=
ash flows but because Trump Media has =E2=80=9CTrump=E2=80=9D in the name, =
is largely owned by Donald Trump, and represents a bet on his electoral for=
tunes and general newsworthiness. Those have gone up recently. Converting T=
rump=E2=80=99s newsworthiness into money is, as far as I can tell, the=C2=
=A0<em>point=C2=A0</em>of Trump Media, and now is the time.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Traditionally the way meme-y companies raise money is with=
 at-the-market stock offerings. In an ATM offering, the company hires a bro=
ker, and the broker sells some stock, at market prices, over the course of =
days or weeks. This is different from a traditional underwritten offering, =
in which the company=E2=80=99s investment bank markets the stock to big inv=
estors, builds an order book, and then sells a chunk of stock all at once, =
at a single price, to all of those investors. The problem with a traditiona=
l underwriting, for a meme stock, is that your banks call up all the profes=
sional investors and say =E2=80=9Chey do you want to buy this stock at a cr=
azy price?=E2=80=9D and the investors say =E2=80=9Cno I do not.=E2=80=9D Be=
ing a meme stock means that=C2=A0<em>retail=C2=A0</em>investors are buying =
the stock at a crazy price, and the big investment banks can=E2=80=99t real=
ly call them all. So meme stocks do ATM offerings, so they can sell the sto=
ck directly on the exchange, where the retail investors are buying it at cr=
azy prices.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so many meme and meme-adjac=
ent stocks =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
