none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">went public in March</a>=
 by merging with a special purpose acquisition company called Digital World=
 Acquisition Corp. The US Securities and Exchange Commission rules only all=
ow companies that have been public for at least 12 months to do at-the-mark=
et offerings, so Trump Media can=E2=80=99t do one until next March.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a solution. The solution is:<=
/p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px =
0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Trump Media sells stock to=C2=A0<e=
m>one=C2=A0</em>investor, over time, at market-based prices.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Each time that=C2=A0<em>one=C2=A0</em>investor b=
uys stock from Trump Media, it can immediately turn around and resell it, o=
n the stock exchange, at market prices.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">It=E2=80=99s meme-stock intermediation, an at-the-market offering done <=
em>through </em>one investor. There are a couple of ways to do this =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0Bed Bath &amp; Beyond once did <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/36091809.196395/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDcvYmVkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLXNvbGQtc29tZS1zdG9j=
az9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzE3MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U=
9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3MTcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB275b2574" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a pretty complicated one</a> =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but a simple one is called an =E2=80=9Cequity line of credit=E2=80=9D=
 or =E2=80=9Cstandby equity purchase agreement=E2=80=9D: The investor signs=
 a deal with the company saying =E2=80=9Cyou can sell us up to $X worth of =
stock, over time, whenever you want, and we=E2=80=99ll pay you the market p=
rice for it less a discount for our trouble.=E2=80=9D And then whenever the=
 company wants money, it calls up the investor and says =E2=80=9Cokay $10 m=
illion today,=E2=80=9D and the investor sells $10 million worth of stock in=
to the market and pays the company $10 million, less its fee. And if the ma=
rket is good and the company wants a lot of money, it makes those calls eve=
ry day, and pretty soon the investor has sold a lot of stock and the compan=
y has raised a lot of money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In these deals=
, the investor is often Yorkville Advisors. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36091809.196395/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
